Chakrans and Dragons on IMDB

EDA on IMDB data about Game of Thrones (GOT) and Xena the Warrior Princess

JosÃ© Benardi de Souza Nunes

Employed data

Exploratory data analysis on IMDB data about TV series. Original data comes from this repository, there we have an explanation on how the data was gathered and the meaning of each variable.

Data under analysis

Before the staggering number of different series available in our data we will analyse the following two:

  • Game of Thrones
  • Xena The Warrior Princess (in portuguese Xena a Princesa Guerreira)

Data Overview

On average how many votes there are for an episode of a season?

episodes %>% 
    filter(series_name %in% c("Xena a Princesa Guerreira")) %>%
    ggplot(aes(x = season_ep, y = user_votes))  + 
    geom_line() +
    facet_wrap(~ season) +
    labs(x="Season episode",
         y= "Number of votes",
         title="Distribution of votes per episode throughout seasons (Xena)")

The series Xena overall had hundreds of votes for each episode throughout its six seasons.

episodes %>% 
    filter(series_name %in% c("Game of Thrones")) %>%
    filter(season != 6) %>%
    ggplot(aes(x = season_ep, y = user_votes))  + 
    geom_line() +
    facet_wrap(~ season) + 
        labs(x="Season episode",
         y= "Number of votes",
         title="Distribution of votes per episode throughout seasons (GOT)")

The series GOT had tenths of thousands of votes for each episode throughout its first five seasons. Furthermore, there are some episodes with a lot more votes than the rest.

episodes %>%

sumario_simples <- episodes %>%

episodes %>% 
    group_by(series_name) %>%
    summarise(
        mean = mean(user_rating),
        sd = sd(user_rating),
        n = n()
    ) %>%
    mutate(se = sd/sqrt(n)) %>%
    ggplot(aes(series_name,mean, fill = series_name)) +
    geom_bar(stat='identity') +
    geom_errorbar(aes(width= 0.25,
                      ymax = mean + se,
                      ymin = mean - se)) +
    scale_fill_discrete(name = "Series name") +
    scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0,10)) +
    labs(y = "Mean user rating") +
    theme(axis.title.x=element_blank(),
          axis.text.x=element_blank(),
          axis.ticks.x=element_blank())

  • Looking at the height of the bars (Mean user rating) itâs noticeble that GOTâs mean user rating is higher than Xenaâs mean user rating.

The mean user rating also suggests that the series Game of Thrones Ã© mais bem avaliada is better rated than the series Xena the Warrior Princess on IMBD, the difference seems to be of 1 point and in terms of series ratings the difference is sizable.

Qual das sÃ©ries tem episÃ³dios mais sem graÃ§a? (Um episÃ³dio Ã© sem graÃ§a se ninguÃ©m nem ama nem odeia ele)

episodes <- episodes %>%
    mutate(
        rank_odiados = row_number(r1), # maior = mais odiado
        rank_amados = row_number(r10), # maior = mais amado
        amado_odiado = rank_amados * rank_odiados) # maior = mais amado E odiado 
episodes %>%

A sÃ©rie Xena apresenta uma grande concentraÃ§Ã£o de episÃ³dios que nÃ£o foram nem amados nem odiados, amado_odiado perto de 0, como mostra claramente o grÃ¡fico de dispersÃ£o, enquanto a sÃ©rie GOT nÃ£o possui episÃ³dios cujo valor amado_odiado esteja perto de 0. Portanto a sÃ©rie Xena Ã© a sÃ©rie com mais episÃ³dios sem graÃ§a.

EpisÃ³dios no inÃ­cio/fim da temporada sÃ£o mais bem avaliados que os no meio?

Consideraremos os 20% iniciais e os 20% finais como o comeÃ§o e fim de temporada, e os 60% entre essas duas parcelas como o meio de temporada. Um episÃ³dio serÃ¡ de metade de temporada se estiver incluido nesses 60%.

sumario_simples <- 
    episodes %>% 
    select(season_ep,season,series_name) %>%
    group_by(series_name,season) %>% 
    summarise(n = n(),
               p20 = quantile(seq(from=1, to=n, by=1), 0.20),
               p80 = quantile(seq(from=1, to=n, by=1), 0.80))
sumario_simples
episodes <- left_join(episodes, sumario_simples,
                      by = c("series_name", "season")) %>% 
    group_by(series_name, season) %>%
    mutate(middle_eps = (season_ep > p20) &
               (season_ep < p80)) %>% 
    ungroup()
episodes


Geramos a informaÃ§Ã£o middle_eps para representar se uma sÃ©rie Ã© ou nÃ£o do meio da temporada, estÃ¡ entre os 20% episÃ³dios inicias e finais da temporada (no meio). Se middle_eps Ã© TRUE o episÃ³dio Ã© da metade da temporada, se middle_eps Ã© FALSE o episÃ³dio Ã© do comeÃ§o/fim da temporada.

filtered <- episodes %>%
    filter(series_name %in% c("Xena a Princesa Guerreira")) %>%
    filter(season == 4)
filtered %>%
    ggplot(aes(x = season_ep, y = user_rating, color = series_name)) +
    geom_vline(xintercept = filtered$p20,
    color = "blue") +
    geom_vline(xintercept = filtered$p80,
    color = "blue") +
    geom_line()

Usando a 4Âª temporada da sÃ©rie Xena como exemplo os episÃ³dios da metade de temporada seriam aqueles entre as barras azuis (20Âº percentil e 80Âº percentil, os quais dividem os valores em 20%-80% e 80%-20% respectivamente e assim o que estÃ¡ entre eles Ã© 60% do total).

episodes %>% 
  ggplot(aes(user_rating, color=middle_eps)) + 
    geom_density()

As formas dos histogramas alisados sÃ£o semelhantes, e o pico de ambos (moda ou valor mais frequente) coincide na nota 8, isso sugere que sem distinguir as sÃ©ries umas das outras os episÃ³dios no inÃ­cio/fim da temporada sÃ£o avaliados semelhantemente aos que estÃ£o no meio da sÃ©rie.
